observations.recommendation:
1. Strictly follow the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of physical count of PPE, Recognition of PPE items found at the station, and existing/missing PPE items and require the Accountant and Property Officer to reconcile their records based on the results of the actual physical inventory and effect necessary adjustments;
2. Adopt the uniform numbering system for property numbers of PPE and require the Property Unit to update the property stickers based on the prescribed format and to include the required information under Section 5.6 and 5.7 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
3. Submit the approved PIP to the COA Audit Team within the prescribed period;
4. Conduct the required preliminary activities prior to inventory taking; and
5. Record/document the physical count daily in a standard ICF prescribed in Annex A of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

14. Direct the Municipal Assessor to coordinate with and seek technical assistance from the Provincial Assessor and/or the DOF-Bureau of Local Government Finance to fast-track the preparation of the updated SMVs of the Municipality pursuant to Section 212 of the LGC and cause the drafting of an Ordinance for consideration of the Sanggunian, incorporating therein the proposed SMV, assessment level and tax rate to support the conduct of GRRPA within the reglementary period;
15. Augment the number of qualified personnel assigned at the Municipal Assessor’s Office to meet the minimum personnel requirements stipulated in the MRPAAO and conduct capacity-building interventions to facilitate the conduct of the GRRPA in adherence to Section 219 of the same Code and DILG-DOF JMC No. 2010-001, and closely monitor its completion; and
16. Make representation with the Local Chief Executive/Local Sanggunian to appropriate funds for the computerization of the assessment records to hasten the completion of GRRPA data gathering and encoding.
